Both Tshwane and Ekurhuleni residents say the municipalities were not transparent enough when it comes to letting them know how long they will be without water. eNCA's Nqobile Madlala reports. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - It's been a long week for some residents in Tshwane and Ekurhuleni. They say the two municipalities could have better-handled communication about water cuts after days without water. Residents say the municipalities were not transparent enough when it comes to letting them know how long they will be without water. READ: Ekurhuleni taps expected to run in 48 hours Water supply to about 90 percent of affected areas have since been restored. In the Ekurhuleni municipality, hundreds of houses had to make do without water for over a week. READ: Most of Tshwane's reservoirs recover The City of Tshwane released a statement stating 90 percent of areas that were without water were getting it now. However, for some households in Ekurhuleni municipality the wait for the water to return continues. * eNCA's Nqobile Madlala reports.